                        "type": "1",
                        "version": 0,
                        "content": "A homeless client is being seen at a local outreach clinic. What action(s) taken by the nurse is best to help ensure the client's adherence and follow-up to the new treatment plan? Select all that apply.",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "a0f7d178f7b728b8bba7ef20ddeca62d",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Evaluating 评价",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nHealth visits for clients in the homeless population would be nonjudgmental and nonthreatening; this will build trust between the caregiver and the client and is more likely to promote adherence to the plan of care. Also, the nurse would focus on reported symptoms first and not what the nurse thinks is a problem, based on subjective findings. Additionally, close monitoring and follow-up may be needed, so helping set up future appointments may help the client have better adherence to the treatment plan and follow-up. Focusing on the obvious health abnormalities and expecting the client to bathe before receiving health care is demeaning.\n\nTest-Taking Strategy:\nNote the strategic word, best. Thinking about the homeless population and their lack of health care access and follow-up will help you select the options that would help promote better client outcomes. Also, note that options 4 and 5 are nontherapeutic.",
                        "id": "f933bba7f1474ffe98527e3114f8df67",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
                    }
                ]
            },
